<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_number` row that
    creates the auto-numbering counter for the `x_[scope]_case` custom table
    inside the scoped application `x_[scope]`.

    This is the most cross-referenced sys_number record in the scoped
    application. Every demo case, every portal-submitted case, every
    dashboard widget that filters by case number, and every seed-data
    lookup-by-number relies on this counter producing the correct format.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim):
        Field   Type            Constraints
        number  Auto-number     Read-only, format CASE0000001

    Per AAP Section 0.7.4 (Other User-Provided Rules) verbatim:
        "Auto-numbering format: the case `number` field MUST use format
         CASE0000001 (7-digit zero-padded) and be Read-only."

    Per AAP Section 0.7.3 (Validation Gates) this record is foundational to
    THREE gates:
      * Gate 1 (Data model): the `number` field on x_[scope]_case follows
        the CASE0000001 format defined HERE.
      * Gate 4 (Portal - submission): the auto-number generated by THIS
        counter is what the portal submission scripted REST endpoint
        returns to the requester; "correct case number" means the format
        matches CASE0000001.
      * Gate 5 (Portal - lookup): the lookup endpoint queries by case
        number; the format must be consistent between submission and
        lookup, both anchored to THIS counter.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
      com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java
        Line 124-128:
            @Id
            @TableGenerator(name = "case_file_gen",
                            table = "acm_case_file_id",
                            pkColumnName = "cm_seq_name",
                            valueColumnName = "cm_seq_num",
                            pkColumnValue = "acm_case_file",
                            initialValue = 100,
                            allocationSize = 1)
            @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.TABLE,
                            generator = "case_file_gen")
            @Column(name = "cm_case_id") private Long id;
        Line 130-132:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_number")
            @AcmSequence(sequenceName = "caseNumberSequence")
            private String caseNumber;
      ArkCase used two parallel mechanisms: @TableGenerator for the JPA
      primary key `id` (Long) AND @AcmSequence for the human-readable
      `caseNumber` (String). The ServiceNow target collapses both into a
      single auto-number counter (THIS record) producing CASE0000001;
      the platform-internal primary key is the separate `sys_id` column.
      Both legacy mechanisms write to bespoke MySQL bookkeeping tables
      (acm_case_file_id, acm_sequence); this record replaces both with
      the platform-native sys_number facility - a single declarative
      low-code equivalent.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: this record's <sys_scope> and
        <sys_package> bind it to the scoped application
        `x_[scope]`. The <table> element points at the
        SCOPED case table `x_[scope]_case` - NOT at the OOB `task`,
        `incident`, or any other global table. NO global-scope writes.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: every cross-reference
        (<sys_scope>, <sys_package>, <table>) resolves by NAME (the
        scope source name `x_[scope]` and the table
        name `x_[scope]_case`), not by literal sys_id. The <sys_id>
        text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (MD5 of the canonical record name `sys_number_x_[scope]_case`)
        and is NOT a reference to any other record.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP convention;
        the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App Engine Studio
        creation time. Do NOT substitute it with a real scope id.
      - <prefix>CASE</prefix> is uppercase, exactly 4 characters, NOT
        `Case`, NOT `case`, NOT `CSE`. Per AAP Section 0.7.4 verbatim,
        `CASE` is the prefix component of the required CASE0000001
        format. The platform's default auto-number padding is 7 digits
        when the prefix is short and the initial maximum is 0, so the
        first generated identifier is CASE0000001 - exactly matching
        the AAP requirement. This mirrors ServiceNow's standard
        convention for similar OOB tables (INC0000001, CHG0000001,
        PRB0000001, SCTASK0000001).
      - <maximum>0</maximum> and <number>0</number>: both starting at 0.
        After the platform processes the first GlideRecord.insert() of an
        x_[scope]_case row, the counter increments to 1 and renders as
        CASE0000001. Successive inserts produce CASE0000002,
        CASE0000003, etc. ArkCase's @TableGenerator initialValue=100 is
        intentionally NOT preserved here: the POC starts the sequence
        cleanly at 1, which is the conventional ServiceNow default.
      - Read-only enforcement is NOT in this file. Per AAP Section 0.7.4
        verbatim: "the case `number` field MUST use format CASE0000001
        (7-digit zero-padded) and be Read-only." The Read-only constraint
        is enforced at the DICTIONARY entry level (in
        ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_number.xml's <read_only>true
        </read_only> setting). THIS sys_number record only configures
        the COUNTER; the dictionary entry configures user-facing field
        behavior.
      - <category>x_[scope]_case</category>: ServiceNow's convention for
        the `category` column on sys_number is to set it to the target
        table name (mirroring the <table> field). This is purely an
        organizational grouping; the platform does not derive runtime
        behavior from it.
      - No PII: the counter stores only synthetic auto-generated
        identifiers (CASE0000001, etc.); no real names, email addresses,
        or organizational identifiers are derived from or stored here.
      - Re-exportability: the deterministic <sys_id> (MD5-derived
        32-char lowercase hex) ensures that re-exporting the Update Set
        produces the same sys_id every time, preventing
        "duplicate-record" errors during fresh-PDI re-import preview
        (AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7).

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      This record MUST load AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record - must exist
          before any scoped record)
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (application
          record - <sys_package> resolves by source name to this)
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml (target table - <table> field
          references it by name)
      This record MUST load BEFORE consumers that read or write the
      `number` column:
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_number.xml (the `number`
          dictionary entry - already references this auto-number record
          indirectly via the parent table's <number_ref>)
        - ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml
          (returns the auto-generated CASE0000001-formatted number to
          the portal requester)
        - ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup.xml
          (queries by case number; depends on the format being correct)
        - All ../seed-data/cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_*.xml records
          (demo cases populate `number` field with synthetic identifiers
          like CASE0000001-CASE0000010, which must align with the
          format produced by this counter)
        - ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js (idempotent server-side seed
          script that uses GlideRecord lookups by case `number`)
-->
<record_update table="sys_number">
    <sys_number action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <category>x_[scope]_case</category>
        <maximum>0</maximum>
        <number>0</number>
        <number_of_digits>7</number_of_digits>
        <prefix>CASE</prefix>
        <sys_class_name>sys_number</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>4fc55a26e01ab60d8ea5ce13ce35f6f3</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_number_x_[scope]_case</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <table>x_[scope]_case</table>
    </sys_number>
</record_update>
